Borrowed

T. Buhler

 

Papery pillows where tall necks

Curve around and combed heads

Rest on the draining bed

Ferociously

 

This is where the weeknights

Pass like grain trains

Through a purple skied

Prairie town

 

Moth dust rattles like

Maracas and sunny sin

The imperial girl shouts

Throwing a hope wrench

 

This is where cancer

Cultivates like lust

In a blue light

Porn shop

Stare It Down

T. Buhler

 

A fall leaf expression hits her face

A reddening death

She sits content

Smiles quiver to life every so often

 

This is quite the balancing act

Tip-toe kitten on a high wire

Making her laugh

Making her cry

 

Pull yourself together

Last hopes drop like flies

This summer heat kills

As fall chills cool

Two Shipwrecks

T. Buhler

 

The little boy noticed the bay

He had lived beside it his entire life

As he walked his wheeled sailboat

He realized the boat belonged on the water

 

He set the little ship off from a small rock

Crouched down, wet bottom

His ship bubbled then sunk

He witnessed this wreck from shore then troddled back into his house

 

His mom was crying, still on the phone

He ran and got her a tissue to wipe her nose

She clicked the phone down and slumped to the floor

That night as they watched the news, both were crying

It Just Happened

T. Buhler

 

Howl home this point of mine

And take a horse and carriage ride

Through the filmy mists surrounding

A vacant iron mine

 

Blazing sparks burst from the thunderbolt

That happened to be pulled from my chest

When the detriment was complete

The night paints its way back in

 

The music decrescendos

From a scarecrow Sinatra

An out-of-tune piano plunks in cadence

With my out of sync pulse

 

If ravens request to sing me to my sleep

Where have your lullabies gone?

And if I fail to notice cadaverous crowds beyond me

Does this mean I am alone?

Boiling Buildings and the Act of Becoming Unraveled

T. Buhler

 

The hot pavement could melt your shoes

Straight to your calloused soles

Heat rippled sun-scrapers shoot out of the pavement

Until the night set in, blisteringly cold, snow sometimes falls

 

I never understood her side of the story

But this is the beginning scene for me

Understand, I used to follow certain rules and guidelines

But they had no substance or will-breaking backbone

 

Call me unqualified or ignorant

But I sold my soul to a prostitute

Heat for one moment and paralyzing cold the next

Did I mention she took my virginity as well?
